3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly Network calculates ENA/USDT funding rates hourly based on the premium/discount to spot prices across its shared order book. The funding mechanism operates through smart contracts on NEAR Protocol, with settlements processed automatically across all connected frontend partners. Rates are determined by the 8-hour TWAP of the perpetual-spot premium, applied every hour to open positions."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","ENA","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ENA's role in Ethena's synthetic dollar protocol creates significant funding rate volatility, especially during USDe demand fluctuations. The shared liquidity model on Orderly means ENA/USDT funding rates often diverge from centralized exchanges due to different user bases and trading patterns across DEX frontends."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Funding Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"ENA/USDT on Orderly Network has shown funding rates ranging from -0.15% to +0.25% hourly during volatile periods. The pair exhibits higher positive funding during USDe yield farming campaigns and negative rates during market downturns. Orderly's shared liquidity across multiple frontends creates smoother rate transitions compared to isolated DEX pairs. The hourly settlement frequency provides more granular arbitrage opportunities than traditional 8-hour cycles."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Cross-DEX Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"The shared order book infrastructure enables arbitrage between Orderly Network and major CEX platforms like Binance or OKX. ENA funding rates on Orderly often lag centralized exchanges by 15-30 minutes due to different user demographics and trading behaviors. Traders can exploit rate differentials by taking opposite positions across platforms, though gas costs on NEAR must be factored into profitability calculations. The multi-chain accessibility through various frontends adds complexity but also diversifies arbitrage entry points."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Management Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Orderly's dependency on frontend partners introduces counterparty risks not present in direct exchange trading. Smart contract risks on NEAR Protocol and potential frontend failures could impact position management during volatile funding periods. The shared liquidity model means sudden large trades on any connected frontend affect the entire order book, potentially causing rapid funding rate changes. Cross-chain bridge risks apply when moving collateral between supported networks for arbitrage positions."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How does Orderly Network's shared liquidity affect ENA funding rates?","answer":"The shared order book aggregates trading activity from multiple DEX frontends, creating deeper liquidity than isolated pairs. This results in more stable funding rates but can create delays in rate adjustments compared to centralized exchanges with direct user access."},{"question":"What are the settlement mechanics for ENA/USDT funding on Orderly?","answer":"Funding settlements occur hourly through NEAR Protocol smart contracts, automatically debiting or crediting positions based on the calculated rate. The process is transparent on-chain but requires sufficient USDT balance in your account to cover negative funding payments."},{"question":"Can I arbitrage ENA funding rates between Orderly frontends?","answer":"No, all frontends share the same order book and funding rates. Arbitrage opportunities exist between Orderly Network as a whole and external exchanges, not between different Orderly-powered DEX interfaces."},{"question":"How do gas costs on NEAR impact ENA funding arbitrage profitability?","answer":"NEAR's low transaction costs (typically under $0.01) make frequent position adjustments viable for funding arbitrage. However, cross-chain bridge fees when moving collateral between networks can significantly impact smaller arbitrage positions."}]}]
